<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-definitions-and-examples-of-integration"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Definitions and Examples</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      We define the Riemann integral by Darboux's approach. The main objects
      are lower and upper sums attached to partitions of a closed bounded
      interval. These sums give step-function approximations to a bounded
      function from below and above, and the function is integrable precisely
      when the gap between these approximations can be made arbitrarily small.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-partitions-and-darboux-sums">
    <title>Partitions and Darboux Sums</title>

    <p>
      A <term>partition</term><idx><h>partition</h><h>of an interval</h></idx>
      of a closed bounded interval <m>[a,b]</m> is a finite subset of
      <m>[a,b]</m> containing both endpoints. We list a partition in
      increasing order:
      <md>
        P=\{x_0,x_1,\dots,x_n\},
        \qquad
        a=x_0 \lt x_1 \lt \cdots \lt x_n=b.
      </md>
      For such a partition, we write
      <md>
        I_i=[x_{i-1},x_i],
        \qquad
        \Delta x_i=x_i-x_{i-1}
        \qquad (1 \le i \le n).
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      For now, we write <m>\int_a^b f</m> rather than
      <m>\int_a^b f(x)\,dx</m>. At this stage there is no risk of confusion,
      because the interval and the function being integrated are both fixed.
      Only later, when we discuss change of variables, will it become useful
      to display the variable of integration explicitly.
    </p>

    <p>
      Now let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> be bounded, and let
      <m>P=\{x_0,\dots,x_n\}</m> be a partition of <m>[a,b]</m>. For each
      subinterval <m>I_i=[x_{i-1},x_i]</m>, define
      <md>
        m_i=\inf\{f(x):x \in I_i\},
        \qquad
        M_i=\sup\{f(x):x \in I_i\}.
      </md>
      The numbers
      <md>
        L(P,f)=\sum_{i=1}^n m_i \Delta x_i
        \qquad\text{and}\qquad
        U(P,f)=\sum_{i=1}^n M_i \Delta x_i
      </md>
      are called the <term>lower Darboux sum</term><idx><h>Darboux
      sum</h><h>lower</h></idx> and <term>upper Darboux sum</term><idx><h>Darboux
      sum</h><h>upper</h></idx> of <m>f</m> with respect to <m>P</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-darboux-sums-x-squared">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x)=x^2</m> on <m>[0,1]</m>, and let
          <m>P=\{0,\frac13,\frac23,1\}</m>. Since <m>f</m> is increasing on
          <m>[0,1]</m>, the infimum on each subinterval occurs at the left
          endpoint and the supremum occurs at the right endpoint. Therefore
          <md>
            L(P,f)
            =
            \left(0+\frac19+\frac49\right)\frac13
            =
            \frac{5}{27},
          </md>
          while
          <md>
            U(P,f)
            =
            \left(\frac19+\frac49+1\right)\frac13
            =
            \frac{14}{27}.
          </md>
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-darboux-sums-x-squared">
          <caption>The lower Darboux sum, the upper Darboux sum, and the
          curve <m>y=x^2</m> for the partition
          <m>\{0,\frac13,\frac23,1\}</m>.</caption>
          <image width="60%">
            <shortdescription>A parabola on the interval from zero to one together with two overlapping families of rectangles for the lower and upper Darboux sums based on the partition at one third and two thirds.</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=9cm,
  height=6cm,
  axis lines=middle,
  xmin=-0.05, xmax=1.05,
  ymin=-0.05, ymax=1.1,
  xtick={0,0.333333,0.666667,1},
  xticklabels={$0$,$\frac13$,$\frac23$,$1$},
  ytick={0,0.111111,0.444444,1},
  yticklabels={$0$,$\frac19$,$\frac49$,$1$},
  xlabel={$x$},
  ylabel={$y$},
  clip=false
]
  \draw[fill=orange!18, draw=orange!60!black] (axis cs:0,0) rectangle (axis cs:0.333333,0.111111);
  \draw[fill=orange!18, draw=orange!60!black] (axis cs:0.333333,0) rectangle (axis cs:0.666667,0.444444);
  \draw[fill=orange!18, draw=orange!60!black] (axis cs:0.666667,0) rectangle (axis cs:1,1);
  \draw[fill=blue!22, draw=blue!60] (axis cs:0,0) rectangle (axis cs:0.333333,0);
  \draw[fill=blue!22, draw=blue!60] (axis cs:0.333333,0) rectangle (axis cs:0.666667,0.111111);
  \draw[fill=blue!22, draw=blue!60] (axis cs:0.666667,0) rectangle (axis cs:1,0.444444);
  \addplot[black, thick, domain=0:1, samples=150] {x^2};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-constant-function-darboux-sums">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f(x)=c</m> is constant on <m>[a,b]</m>, then for every
          partition <m>P</m> we have <m>m_i=M_i=c</m> for every
          <m>i</m>. Hence
          <md>
            L(P,f)=c(b-a)=U(P,f).
          </md>
          So lower and upper sums already agree for every partition.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-upper-and-lower-integrals">
    <title>Upper and Lower Integrals</title>

    <p>
      Since <m>f</m> is bounded, there exist real numbers <m>m \le M</m> such
      that
      <md>
        m \le f(x) \le M
        \qquad (x \in [a,b]).
      </md>
      Therefore, for every partition <m>P</m>,
      <md>
        m(b-a) \le L(P,f) \le U(P,f) \le M(b-a).
      </md>
      Thus the set of all lower sums is bounded above, and the set of all
      upper sums is bounded below.
    </p>

    <p>
      By the
      <xref ref="ax-least-upper-bound-property" text="title"/>, the least upper bound
      of the set of lower sums exists, and likewise the greatest lower bound
      of the set of upper sums exists. We define the
      <term>lower integral</term><idx><h>integral</h><h>lower</h></idx> and
      <term>upper integral</term><idx><h>integral</h><h>upper</h></idx> of
      <m>f</m> by
      <md>
        \underline{\int_a^b} f
        :=
        \sup\{L(P,f): P \text{ a partition of } [a,b]\},
      </md>
      and
      <md>
        \overline{\int_a^b} f
        :=
        \inf\{U(P,f): P \text{ a partition of } [a,b]\}.
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      If <m>P</m> and <m>P'</m> are partitions of <m>[a,b]</m>, we say that
      <m>P'</m> is a <term>refinement</term><idx><h>partition</h><h>refinement</h></idx>
      of <m>P</m> if <m>P \subseteq P'</m>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-refinement-monotonicity-darboux-sums">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> be bounded. If <m>P'</m> is a
          refinement of <m>P</m>, then
          <md>
            L(P,f) \le L(P',f) \le U(P',f) \le U(P,f).
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          It is enough to prove the result in the special case where <m>P'</m>
          is obtained from <m>P=\{x_0,\dots,x_n\}</m> by adjoining a single
          point <m>x'</m> with <m>x_{i-1} \lt x' \lt x_i</m> for some
          <m>i</m>. All terms in the upper sum remain unchanged except the
          term corresponding to the interval <m>[x_{i-1},x_i]</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Let <m>M</m> be the supremum of <m>f</m> on <m>[x_{i-1},x_i]</m>,
          and let <m>M_1,M_2</m> be the suprema on
          <m>[x_{i-1},x']</m> and <m>[x',x_i]</m>, respectively. Since these
          two intervals are contained in <m>[x_{i-1},x_i]</m>, we have
          <m>M_1 \le M</m> and <m>M_2 \le M</m>. Therefore
          <md>
            M_1(x'-x_{i-1}) + M_2(x_i-x')
            \le
            M\bigl((x'-x_{i-1})+(x_i-x')\bigr)
            =
            M(x_i-x_{i-1}).
          </md>
          So <m>U(P',f) \le U(P,f)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          The proof that <m>L(P,f) \le L(P',f)</m> is analogous, using
          infima instead of suprema. The middle inequality
          <m>L(P',f) \le U(P',f)</m> is immediate.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-lower-upper-integral-between-sums">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For every partition <m>P</m> of <m>[a,b]</m>,
          <md>
            L(P,f)
            \le
            \underline{\int_a^b} f
            \le
            \overline{\int_a^b} f
            \le
            U(P,f).
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>P</m> and <m>P'</m> be any two partitions. Then
          <m>P \cup P'</m> is a common refinement of both. By
          <xref ref="prop-refinement-monotonicity-darboux-sums"/>,
          <md>
            L(P,f) \le L(P \cup P',f) \le U(P \cup P',f) \le U(P',f).
          </md>
          Since <m>P'</m> is arbitrary, <m>L(P,f)</m> is a lower bound for the
          set of upper sums. Hence
          <m>L(P,f) \le \overline{\int_a^b} f</m>. Therefore every
          upper integral is an upper bound for the set of lower sums, so
          <m>\underline{\int_a^b} f \le \overline{\int_a^b} f</m>.
          The remaining inequalities follow directly from the definitions of
          supremum and infimum.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <example xml:id="eg-dirichlet-upper-lower-integrals">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Define the Dirichlet function <m>1_{\Q} \colon [0,1] \to \R</m> by
          <md>
            1_{\Q}(x)=
            \begin{cases}
              1 &amp; \text{if } x \in \Q,\\
              0 &amp; \text{if } x \notin \Q.
            \end{cases}
          </md>
          Then
          <md>
            \underline{\int_0^1} 1_{\Q} = 0
            \qquad\text{and}\qquad
            \overline{\int_0^1} 1_{\Q} = 1.
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Indeed, by <xref ref="prop-q-dense-in-r"/>, every nondegenerate
          subinterval of <m>[0,1]</m> contains a rational number. If
          <m>[u,v]</m> is such a subinterval, then
          <m>[u-\sqrt{2},v-\sqrt{2}]</m> is also nondegenerate, so again by
          <xref ref="prop-q-dense-in-r"/> there is some <m>q \in \Q</m> with
          <m>u-\sqrt{2} \lt q \lt v-\sqrt{2}</m>. Then
          <m>q+\sqrt{2}</m> is irrational and lies in <m>[u,v]</m>. Thus on
          each subinterval of any partition the infimum is <m>0</m> and the
          supremum is <m>1</m>. Hence every lower sum is <m>0</m> and every
          upper sum is <m>1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-riemann-integrability-darboux">
    <title>Riemann Integrability</title>

    <p>
      A bounded function <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> is
      <term>Riemann integrable</term><idx>Riemann integrable function</idx> if
      its lower and upper integrals are equal:
      <md>
        \underline{\int_a^b} f
        =
        \overline{\int_a^b} f.
      </md>
      The common value is called the <term>Riemann integral</term><idx><h>Riemann
      integral</h><h>value of</h></idx> of <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>, and is
      denoted by
      <md>
        \int_a^b f.
      </md>
      We write <m>R[a,b]</m> for the set of all Riemann integrable functions on
      <m>[a,b]</m>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-integrability-criterion-darboux">
      <title>Integrability Criterion</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A bounded function <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> is Riemann
          integrable if and only if for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there
          exists a partition <m>P</m> of <m>[a,b]</m> such that
          <md>
            U(P,f)-L(P,f) \lt \varepsilon.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          First assume that for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists a
          partition <m>P</m> with <m>U(P,f)-L(P,f) \lt \varepsilon</m>. By
          <xref ref="cor-lower-upper-integral-between-sums"/>,
          <md>
            0
            \le
            \overline{\int_a^b} f
            -
            \underline{\int_a^b} f
            \le
            U(P,f)-L(P,f).
          </md>
          Since the right-hand side can be made arbitrarily small, the
          difference of the upper and lower integrals must be <m>0</m>. Hence
          <m>f</m> is integrable.
        </p>

        <p>
          Conversely, suppose <m>f</m> is integrable, and let
          <m>I=\int_a^b f</m>. Given <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, choose
          partitions <m>P'</m> and <m>P''</m> such that
          <md>
            U(P',f) \lt I+\frac{\varepsilon}{2}
            \qquad\text{and}\qquad
            I-\frac{\varepsilon}{2} \lt L(P'',f).
          </md>
          Let <m>P=P' \cup P''</m>. Then <m>P</m> refines both <m>P'</m> and
          <m>P''</m>, so
          <md>
            I-\frac{\varepsilon}{2}
            \lt
            L(P'',f)
            \le
            L(P,f)
            \le
            U(P,f)
            \le
            U(P',f)
            \lt
            I+\frac{\varepsilon}{2}.
          </md>
          Therefore <m>U(P,f)-L(P,f) \lt \varepsilon</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-x-integrable-on-unit-interval">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The function <m>f(x)=x</m> is Riemann integrable on <m>[0,1]</m>.
          For each <m>n \in \N</m>, let
          <md>
            P_n=\left\{0,\frac{1}{n},\frac{2}{n},\dots,\frac{n-1}{n},1\right\}.
          </md>
          Since <m>f</m> is increasing,
          <md>
            L(P_n,f)
            =
            \frac{1}{n^2}\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} k
            =
            \frac{n-1}{2n}
          </md>
          and
          <md>
            U(P_n,f)
            =
            \frac{1}{n^2}\sum_{k=1}^{n} k
            =
            \frac{n+1}{2n}.
          </md>
          Hence
          <md>
            U(P_n,f)-L(P_n,f)=\frac{1}{n} \to 0.
          </md>
          By the <xref ref="prop-integrability-criterion-darboux" text="title"/>,
          the function <m>x</m> is integrable on <m>[0,1]</m>. Also,
          <md>
            \frac{n-1}{2n}
            \le
            \int_0^1 x
            \le
            \frac{n+1}{2n}
          </md>
          for every <m>n</m>, so letting <m>n \to \infty</m> gives
          <md>
            \int_0^1 x = \frac12.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      Finally, if <m>f</m> is integrable on <m>[a,b]</m>, we extend the
      notation by setting
      <md>
        \int_a^a f = 0,
        \qquad
        \int_b^a f = -\int_a^b f.
      </md>
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
